Lunch:

Lafayette County Health Department
July 8 at 3:24 PM ¬∑

LCHD has learned of a confirmed positive case of COVID-19 at the Higginsville Family Aquatic Center Sunday, July 5th from 2:30-4:30. If you were at the pool at this time, please monitor for symptoms.

Symptoms include: Fever, Headache, Chills, Nausea/Vomiting, Muscle Aches, Runny Nose, Sore Throat, Loss of Taste/Smell, Diarrhea, Stomach Pain, Cough, Shortness of Breath.

Symptoms may present 2 to 14 days from exposure. If you have any of these symptoms we recommend you get tested or call your primary care physician. If you need testing site information, please call the health department at 660-259-4371.

Happy Juneteenth!

Juneteenth represents freedom and marks the day, June 19, 1865, when the last of enslaved African-Americans learned that they had been emancipated 2 1/2 years prior.

Learn more at https://nmaahc.si.edu/blog-post/historical-legacy-juneteenth

Today, we celebrate "School Lunch Hero Day!" Between preparing healthy food, adhering to strict nutrition standards, navigating student food allergies, and offering service with a smile, Missouri nutrition professionals have a lot on their plate on a ‚Äúnormal‚Äù day. April 28 at 6:42 PM ¬∑

2020-2021 Choir Auditions! During this time of social-distancing, music has been an important part of so many people's lives. What better way to head back into the new school year than to join a musical ensemble? Choir promotes a creative outlet, self-confidence, community, teamwork, and so much more

An email was sent to students who will be in grades 9-12 with information about how to apply to be a member of Blue and Gold Singers or Women's Choir. Please help encourage students to apply to be in one of these wonderful ensembles by filling out the Google Form found in an email from Mrs. Cook. If students have questions, they may email cooksa@huskersk12.org

**EDIT** Students currently in Blue and Gold or Women‚Äôs Choir wanting to be in the same class don‚Äôt need to re-audition.

post_text:
Senior Spotlight: Lorelai Buford

*Parents: Chad & Kristin Buford

*Plans after HS: Johnson County Community College for two years and then to Kansas State to major in Biology and Microbiology.

*Favorite teachers: I wouldn't say I have one favorite teacher as they've all made an impact over the course of the last fours years, but I feel that Mrs. Reuther, Mrs. Bertz, Mr. Brock, Mrs. Felix, and Mrs. Yoder are teachers that I've really connected with and have spent a lot of time learning from them. Thank you for everything!

*Favorite food: Sushi

*Favorite HS memory: When Jose Gonzalez flipped a water bottle right in the middle of the light above the science wing doors when we were unloading the band trailer. It quickly became a running joke between the band members. My favorite thing about this is that the bottle stayed there for about 2 and a half years and survived tornado strength winds, winter storms, and everything else Missouri weather has to offer.

*In 10 years: Travel the world and enjoy what different cultures and countries have to offer

post_text:
Senior Spotlight: Colette Elizabeth Strathman

*Parents: Kent Strathman & Maria Strathman

*Plans after HS: Major in Nutritional Sciences at Cornell University

*Favorite teacher: It's super hard to choose a favorite teacher. Several teachers in high school have made unique and strong influences in my life. I've learned that most teachers want to do their best to help students! I promise, it doesn't go unnoticed.

*Favorite food: Currently, my favorite food is runny fried eggs. Weird, I know!

*Favorite HS memory: All of my favorite memories happened during school trips! If I had to choose, my most fond memory was going to the FCCLA state conference to run for state office and meeting all of the other incoming officers for the first time.

*In 10 years: I see myself working as a sports dietitian either in a gym I own or in a well known gym, married, getting the chance to travel often, and somehow giving back to the community. I would love to start a scholarship for students going to Lafayette County C-1.

ATTENTION SENIOR PARENTS! Please share this post to help spread the word.

I have had several inquiries about printing yard signs for seniors, so here is some information.....

All yard signs are 18x24, printed on two sides, and come with a yard stake. They are customized with name, photo, and school colors. You are welcome to use a Senior photo that I have taken or if you have a different photo that you would like to use I will need a copyright release. Yard signs are $20 each.

The first bulk order will go in THIS FRIDAY AT 3:00! I will be able to order more at a later date depending on the demand.

All orders can be placed through the School/Sports tab on my website, www.purelifephotography.biz, or paid through Venmo. Feel free to pm me regarding which photo you would like. Delivery will be porch pickup from my house, or I will gladly deliver as many as I can.

I am including three design options. Feel free to contact me with any questions!!!

Gina Kouril Amber Simpson Hope Schloman Siegworth Jamie Harris Iles Cheri Roberts Kristy Gash

Middle school and high school students can pick up their Chromebook or charger only on Monday, March 30 outside of their respective offices. To ensure safety, please adhere to the following schedule and while you are on building grounds, please stay in your vehicles and practice social distancing.

Student last names beginning A-E - 8 to 8:30
Student last names beginning F-J - 8:30 to 9
Student last names beginning K-O - 1 to 1:30
Student last names beginning P-T - 1:30 to 2
Student last names beginning U-Z - 2 to 2:30

If you have problems with internet access, our school-issued devices can still connect to our district Wifi by driving up to the exterior of the building. Please feel free to use this resource.

Questions? Contact central office at 660-584-3631.

post_text:
COVID-19 Update: 3.16.2020

School will be closed until March 24, 2020. More information will be sent as decisions are made.

Food Service:
-Starting Tuesday, March 17th, our district will be serving grab-n-go breakfast and lunch. Breakfast served between 8:00 and 9:00 and lunch is served between 11:00 and 12:00. Pick up locations will be Grandview Elementary (under the preschool awning), Grace UMC parking lot (15th and Walnut, Higginsville), and City of Corder City Hall. No cost to anyone under 18 and to adults with disabilities under 21.

Medications
-If parents need access to medications stored at school, the nurses office at GV and MS/HS will be open on Tuesday, March 17th, from 12-4 for medication pick up.

post_text:
We will be having a two hour delay on Thursday, January 23. As a result, school for grades K-12 will start at 10:00am.

‚Ä¢Students may arrive to school no earlier than 9:30am. Breakfast will be served starting at 9:30am

‚Ä¢All bus pick-up times will be pushed back 2 hours. Example: If the bus pick-up time is normally 7:15am it will be pushed back to 9:15am

‚Ä¢Morning pre-school classes will be cancelled. Afternoon pre-school classes will begin as regularly scheduled

‚Ä¢There will be no Vo-Tech classes in the event of a late start. Vo-Tech students will report to school at 11:00am

‚Ä¢Lunch will be served at regular times

HS Character Dare for this week:
Positive Polly - Do not make a negative comment for the entire week. This means no gossip, no complaining, and no whining. Each time you catch yourself saying something negative, take note of it and see if you can identify why you are doing it. Consider how you might prevent yourself from negative comments in the future. #HuskerStrong #CharacterStrong

Each time you catch yourself saying something negative, take note of it and see if you can identify why you are doing it. Consider how you might prevent yourself from negative comments in the future. #HuskerStrong #CharacterStrong

post_text:
It's World Mental Health day. Our mental health is just like our physical health. We need to take care of our mental health and well-being whether we have a mental health problem or not. That includes our emotional, psychological, and social well-being. It affects how we think, feel, and act. At times, we feel stressed, upset or find it difficult to cope. As we are all different, what affects someone's mental well-being won't necessarily affect others in the same way.World Mental Health Day is observed on 10th October every year, with the overall objective of raising awareness of mental health issues around the world and mobilizing efforts in support of mental health.
#MentalHealthMatters

I am super proud of Sydney Ritter and her accomplishments tonight! She took 2nd place at UCM in the Refresh, Repurpose and Recycle Fashion Design Show. Sydney entered the Repurpose category. She was required to purchase clothing from a thrift store and redesign it into another piece. I admire her creative side and only wish some of it came from me! Her model, Savannah Skinner, did an amazing job of showing off her work. A huge thank you to Sydney‚Äôs advisor, Courtney Bergsieker, who encouraged Sydney to enter her work and took time away from her own family to support her. It‚Äôs wonderful teachers like Courtney who help to inspire our children to be more than they believe possible.

post_text:
We will be having a two hour delay on Monday, March 4. As a result, school for grades K-12 will start at 10:00am.

‚Ä¢Students may arrive to school no earlier than 9:30am. Breakfast will be served starting at 9:30am

‚Ä¢All bus pick-up times will be pushed back 2 hours. Example: If the bus pick-up time is normally 7:15am it will be pushed back to 9:15am

‚Ä¢Morning pre-school classes will be cancelled. Afternoon pre-school classes will begin as regularly scheduled

‚Ä¢There will be no Vo-Tech classes in the event of a late start. Vo-Tech students will report to school at 11:00am

‚Ä¢Lunch will be served at regular times

shared_text:
Courtney Bergsieker is with Glen Kolkmeyer and Todd Whitney.
February 6, 2019 at 6:44 PM ¬∑

Today I had the privilege of accompanying these FCCLA members to Legislative Shadowing at our capitol. Jacob Herera shadowed Representative Glen Kolkmeyer and Brittney Kerley shadowed Senator Denny Hoskins. I was very pleased to see both introduced on the floors! Jacob said he most enjoyed hearing discussion in his committee meeting about MoDot funding. Brittney even got to sit at the head seat of the Senate because Senator Hoskins is the President Pro Tempore! As one of their constituents, seeing them really care about our kids and make them feel special today assured them my future vote. Thank you Representative Kolkmeyer and Senator Hoskins for making their day!
